# [REGEXT](../wg/regext.html)

**IETF 125 - REGEXT Working Group Minutes**

## Summary
The REGEXT working group met at IETF 125 to discuss progress on various RDAP and EPP extensions. Key topics included the transition of JSContact to the Standards Track, the state of EPP over HTTPS/QUIC transports, the introduction of RPKI data into RDAP, and proposed updates to handle verified contacts and same-entity sets. The group also addressed a technical error found in RFC 9803.

## Key Discussion Points

### Working Group Document Updates
*   **[draft-ietf-regext-rdap-jscontact](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/draft-ietf-regext-rdap-jscontact/)**: Mario Loffredo reported that the draft has been moved back to the Standards Track per consensus. The "experiment" section was removed. A minor nit identified by Martin Hoffmann will be fixed in version -04, after which it will be ready for Working Group Last Call (WGLC).
*   **[draft-ietf-regext-epp-quic](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/draft-ietf-regext-epp-quic/)**: James Gould noted that version -04 incorporates feedback from the QUIC working group (Martin Thomson). The chairs will ask the mailing list if there are objections to decoupling this draft from the EPP over HTTPS draft for WGLC.
*   **RDAP Extensions Coordination**: James Gould, Andy Newton, Jazdeep Singh, and Tom Harrison will meet to ensure compatibility between [draft-ietf-regext-rdap-versioning](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/draft-ietf-regext-rdap-versioning/), [draft-ietf-regext-rdap-x-media-type](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/draft-ietf-regext-rdap-x-media-type/), and [draft-ietf-regext-rdap-extensions](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/draft-ietf-regext-rdap-extensions/). The extensions draft remains the priority.
*   **[draft-ietf-regext-rdap-referrals](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/draft-ietf-regext-rdap-referrals/)**: Gavin Brown noted the HTTP Directorate review is complete. He requested more community feedback as the draft significantly changes how RDAP clients interact with servers.
*   **[draft-ietf-regext-balance](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/draft-ietf-regext-balance/)**: Agnieszka Werner has joined as a co-editor. A new version (-01) is forthcoming to address list feedback.

### Presentations

#### 1. [RDAP RPKI Extension Update](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/125/materials/slides-125-regext-rdap-rpki-extension-update-00)
**Presenter: Jazdeep Singh**
*   **Draft:** [draft-ietf-regext-rdap-rpki](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/draft-ietf-regext-rdap-rpki/)
*   **Summary:** Update on version -03. Changes include renaming members to align with Cedarops working group profiles, adding SHA-256/512 message digests for RPKI objects, and introducing the `rdap-help` link relation type.
*   **Discussion:** Rick Wilhelm and Andy Newton discussed the general utility of the `rdap-help` relation type. Jazdeep confirmed it was inspired by Mark Nottingham’s suggestion to prefix new relation types with `rdap-`.
*   **Status:** ARIN has prototyped 35+ lookup/search paths. An implementation status section will be added before WGLC.

#### 2. [draft-ietf-regext-epp-https](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/125/materials/slides-125-regext-draft-ietf-regext-epp-https-00)
**Presenter: Mario Loffredo**
*   **Draft:** [draft-ietf-regext-epp-https](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/draft-ietf-regext-epp-https/)
*   **Summary:** Addressed HTTP Directorate concerns regarding BCP 56 compliance. The directorate suggested using the `CONNECT` method or mapping EPP semantics to HTTP methods. The authors argue that EPP is a stateful transport mapping, not a new HTTP native application, and thus BCP 56's stateless recommendations are a poor fit.
*   **Discussion:** James Gould reported a productive meeting with Mark Nottingham, who appeared receptive to the specific use case of leveraging HTTP as a transport for an existing stateful protocol. Andy Newton emphasized that registrars (who bear the implementation burden) should provide input. Martin Hoffmann noted that comparing this to DNS over HTTPS (DoH) is difficult because EPP is stateful.

#### 3. [IETF 125 REGEXT Kowalik draft-loffredo-regext-rdap-verified-contacts](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/125/materials/slides-125-regext-ietf-125-regext-kowalik-draft-loffredo-regext-rdap-verified-contacts-00)
**Presenter: Pavel Kowalik**
*   **Draft:** draft-loffredo-regext-rdap-verified-contacts
*   **Summary:** Provides a standardized way to represent the verification status of contact data in RDAP, aligned with OpenID Connect/ID4me.
*   **Discussion:** Gavin Brown suggested that IANA’s feedback regarding the reorganization of the JSON values registry should be handled in a separate document. He also questioned the "extensible extension" element as potentially over-complex for clients.
*   **Outcome:** A sense of the room indicated no objections to adoption. The chairs will move the adoption call to the mailing list.

#### 4. [Updating RFC 9803](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/125/materials/slides-125-regext-updating-rfc-9803-00)
**Presenter: Gavin Brown**
*   **Context:** An error was discovered in the XML schema of RFC 9803 (it erroneously limits custom resource records to a single entry).
*   **Discussion:** Gavin proposed updating the namespace from `TTR 1.0` to `TTR 1.1` to avoid interoperability issues where a client might send multiple records to a server expecting only one. James Gould argued this was a minor mistake rather than a material change and questioned the need for a namespace change.
*   **Show of Hands:** A poll showed 13 in favor of changing the namespace and 1 against. 
*   **Decision:** The group will produce a "biz" version of the document to fix the schema, but it is not considered an urgent priority.

#### 5. [Same Entity Set Support for EPP](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/125/materials/slides-125-regext-same-entity-set-support-for-epp-00)
**Presenter: James Galvin (as individual)**
*   **Draft:** draft-ietf-regext-same-entity-set-support-for-epp (Note: Context list shows [draft-ietf-regext-rdap-extensions](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/draft-ietf-regext-rdap-extensions/) or related work, but the presenter referred to the "Same Entity" work).
*   **Summary:** The draft was revised to improve terminology (moving from "variants" to "Same Entity Sets") and to clarify that registry policy defines equivalence.
*   **Discussion:** James Gould requested the inclusion of the XML schema and concrete examples. Antoine Verschuren and Edmund Chung raised questions about how policy changes (e.g., grandfathered/exempt names) affect the protocol. Gavin Brown noted that some registries might want to allow changing the "primary" object of a set, which the current draft restricts.
*   **Outcome:** The chairs will issue a call for adoption on the mailing list.

